subSubSection.paragraph:
Head. Anteclypeus­maxillary plate suture shorter than anteclypeus­loral plate suture; anteoculus shorter than interoculus; eyes triangular, longer than wide (
Fig. 2
); segment I of beak distinctly shorter than segment II (
Fig. 3 a
).

Thorax. Prosternal keel acutely pointed, projecting anterad (
Fig. 3 b
). Front tarsus onesegmented, with vestigial claws. Hind legs sub­quadrate in cross­ section and with hydrofuge hairs and spines, densely arranged.

Abdomen. Pilosity covering almost half of laterotergites and sides of genital operculum; with fold arising from basal angle of genital operculum, this fold subdividing fifth and sixth sternites (
Fig. 4
). Air straps separated from abdominal middle line.

Male genitalia. Ventral diverticulum curved ventrad, fused with aedeagus (
Fig. 5
), and distally slightly concave (
Fig. 6
). Phallobase covering ventral diverticulum at thickened lateral margins (
Figs. 5, 7
).
